Looking at this proof goal, I need to show that `k < L[j].length` where:
- `j := (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (· > i) - 1`
- `k := i - (L.take j).flatten.length`

The key insight is that `j` is the index of the first list in `L` where the cumulative length exceeds `i`. This means `i` falls within the range corresponding to `L[j]`.

Let me trace through the logic:
1. `findIdx (· > i)` finds the first position in `partialSums` where the cumulative sum exceeds `i`
2. This position minus 1 gives us the list index `j` where element `i` actually belongs
3. `k` is the offset within that list
4. We need to show this offset is valid

The proof involves showing that `i < (L.take (j+1)).flatten.length` which equals `(L.take j).flatten.length + L[j].length`, so `k < L[j].length`.

```lean
theorem getElem_flatten_aux₂ (L : List (List α)) (i : Nat) (h : i < L.flatten.length) :
    let j := (L.map length).partialSums.findIdx (· > i) - 1
    have hj : j < L.length := getElem_flatten_aux₁ L i h
    let k := i - (L.take j).flatten.length
    k < L[j].length := by
  intro j hj k
  have h1 : (L.map length).partialSums[j+1] > i := by
    have := findIdx_get (L.map length).partialSums (· > i)
    simp at this
    by_cases w : findIdx (fun x => decide (x > i)) (map length L).partialSums = 0
    · simp [w] at j; omega
    · have := this ⟨_, w⟩
      simp [j] at this ⊢
      omega
  have h2 : (L.map length).partialSums[j] ≤ i := by
    by_cases w : j = 0
    · simp [w]
    · have := findIdx_get_not (L.map length).partialSums (· > i) (j) (by omega)
      simp at this ⊢
      omega
  simp [getElem_partialSums] at h1 h2
  rw [length_flatten, sum_take] at h1 h2
  simp [length_flatten, sum_take, k]
  omega
```
